# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aircraft-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] A **variable cycle engine** (**VCE**), also referred to as **adaptive cycle engine** (**ACE**), is an aircraft jet engine that is designed to operate efficiently under mixed flight conditions, such as subsonic, transonic and supersonic.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] An **advanced technology engine** is a turbine engine that allows different turbines to spin at different, individually optimum speeds, instead of at one speed for all.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] It emerged on larger airplanes, before finding other applications.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The next generation of supersonic transport (SST) may require some form of VCE.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] To reduce aircraft drag at supercruise, SST engines require a high specific thrust (net thrust/airflow) to minimize the powerplant's cross-sectional area.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] This implies a high jet velocity during supersonic cruise and at take-off, which makes the aircraft noisy.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] So for zero flight velocity, specific thrust is directly proportional to jet velocity.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The Rolls-Royce/Snecma Olympus 593 in Concorde had a high specific thrust in supersonic cruise and at dry take-off.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The problem was compounded by the need for a modest amount of afterburning (reheat) at take-off (and transonic acceleration).
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] One SST VCE concept is the tandem fan engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The engine has two fans, both mounted on the low-pressure shaft, separated by a significant axial gap.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The engine operates in series mode while cruising and parallel mode while take-off, climb-out, approach, and final-descent.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In series mode, air enters in the front of the engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] After passing through the front fan, the air passes directly into the second fan, so that the engine behaves much like a turbofan.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In parallel mode, air leaving the front fan exits the engine through an auxiliary nozzle on the underside of the nacelle, skipping the rear fan.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Intakes on each side of the engine open to capture air and send it directly to the rear fan and the rest of the engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Parallel mode substantially increases the total air accelerated by the engine, lowering the velocity of the air and accompanying noise.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In the 1970s, Boeing modified a Pratt & Whitney JT8D to use a tandem fan configuration and successfully demonstrated the switch from series to parallel operation (and vice versa) with the engine running, albeit at partial power.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In the mid-tandem fan concept, a high specific flow single stage fan is located between the high pressure (HP) and low pressure (LP) compressors of a turbojet core.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The LP compressor exit flow passes through passages within the fan disc, directly underneath the fan blades.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Some bypass air enters the engine via an auxiliary intake.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] During take-off and approach the engine behaves much like a conventional turbofan, with an acceptable jet noise level (i.e., low specific thrust).
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] However, for supersonic cruise, the fan variable inlet guide vanes and auxiliary intake close to minimize bypass flow and increase specific thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In this mode the engine acts more like a 'leaky' turbojet (e.g. the F404).
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In the mixed-flow turbofan with ejector concept, a low bypass ratio engine is mounted in front of a long tube, called an ejector.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] It is deployed during take-off and approach.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Turbofan exhaust gases send air into the ejector via an auxiliary air intake, thereby reducing the specific thrust/mean jet velocity of the final exhaust.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The mixed-flow design is not particularly efficient at low speed, but is considerably simpler.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The three-stream architecture adds a third, directable air stream.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] This stream bypasses the core when fuel efficiency is required or through the core for greater power.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Examples include the General Electric XA100 and the Pratt & Whitney XA101, as well as the propulsion system for the Next Generation Air Dominance (NGAD) fighter.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] General Electric developed a variable cycle engine, known as the GE37 or General Electric YF120, for the YF-22/YF-23 fighter aircraft competition, in the late 1980s.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] GE used a double bypass/hybrid fan arrangement, but never disclosed how they exploited the concept.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The Air Force instead selected the conventional Pratt & Whitney F119 for what became the Lockheed Martin F-22 Raptor.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Geared turbofans are also used in the following engines, some still in development: Garrett TFE731, Lycoming ALF 502/LF 507, Pratt & Whitney PW1000G, Turbomeca Astafan, and Turbomeca Aspin, and Aviadvigatel PD-18R.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The Rolls Royce Ultrafan is the largest and most efficient engine to allow multiple turbine speeds.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Startup Astro Mechanica is developing what it calls a turboelectric-adaptive jet engine that shifts from turbofan to turbojet to ramjet mode as it accelerates from a standing start to a projected Mach 6.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] This is achieved by using a dual turbine approach.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The second turbine acts as the propulsion unit.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The turbogenerator powers an electric motor that controls the compressor of the second turbine.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The motor can change speeds to keep the fan turning at the ideal RPM for a specific flight mode.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In turbojet and ramjet modes, the inlet is narrowed to compress the air and eliminate bypass.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The turbogenerator is commercially available, while the propulsion unit is built by the company.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] A key innovation is that electric motors have dramatically increased their power density so that the weight of the motor is no longer prohibitive.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Instead of a fixed gearbox, it uses an electric motor to turn the turbine(s) behind the fan at an ideal speed for each phase of flight.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The company claimed it would support efficient take-off, subsonic, supersonic, and hypersonic speeds.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The electric motor is powered by a generator in turn powered by a turbine.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The approach relies on the improved power density of novel electric motors such as yokeless dual-rotor axial flux motors that offer far more kw/kg than conventional designs that were too heavy for such an application.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] Air flows in through a turbogenerator to produce electric power to power an electric motor.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] The electric motor adaptively controls the propulsion unit, allowing it to behave like a turbofan, turbojet, or ramjet depending on airspeed.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] In effect the engine can operate at any point along the specific impulse (Isp) curve - high Isp at low speed or low Isp at high speed.
[src:aircraft-engine/advanced-technology-engine] It is in some respects similar to turbo-electric marine engines that allow propellers to turn at a different speed than the steam turbines that power them.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] An **aero-engined car** is an automobile powered by an engine designed for aircraft use.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Most such cars have been built for racing, and many have attempted to set world land speed records.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] While the practice of fitting cars with aircraft engines predates World War I by a few years, it was most popular in the interwar period between the world wars when military-surplus aircraft engines were readily available and used to power numerous high-performance racing cars.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Initially powered by piston aircraft engines, a number of post-World War II aero-engined cars have been powered by aviation turbine and jet engines instead.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Piston-engined, turbine-engined, and jet-engined cars have all set world land speed records.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] There have also been some non-racing automotive applications for aircraft engines, including production vehicles such as the Tucker 48 and prototypes such as the Chrysler Turbine Car, Fiat Turbina, and General Motors Firebirds.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In the late 20th century and into the 21st century, there has also been a revival of interest in piston-powered aero-engined racing cars.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In the early 20th century, automotive engines were fairly limited in terms of revolutions per minute (rpm), with 3,000 rpm constituting an upper limit.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] This meant that the easiest way to increase the power output of an engine was to increase its displacement.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In the decade of the 1900s, engine construction necessitated extremely large displacements in order to simply reach the 100 horsepower (75 kW) mark.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Furthermore, while it was difficult to fit such a large engine into a car, it was very much possible, and the fact that most of the aircraft engines of the period were liquid-cooled made them more adaptable for automotive use.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] A number of early European automobile manufacturers experimented with the automotive use of aircraft engines, including Hispano-Suiza, Renault, and Rolls-Royce, although it was Fiat that made perhaps the first true aero-engined car when it created the Tipo S76 in 1910.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Nicknamed "The Beast of Turin", the vehicle consisted of a 1907–08 Fiat production chassis mated to a four-cylinder Tipo S76DA airship engine that had a displacement of 28.4 liters (1,730 cu in) and developed 300 hp (220 kW) at 1,500 rpm.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Daryl Murphy speculates that the car was built to capture the world land speed record, which at the time stood at 125.95 mph (202.70 km/h) after the Blitzen Benz had established the mark at the English track Brooklands in 1909.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] While the Tipo S76 did race at Brooklands, it never exceeded more than about 90 mph (140 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] It later returned to continental Europe and ultimately disappeared during World War I.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Sunbeam also manufactured aircraft engines before World War I, and at the suggestion of chief designer Louis Coatalen it decided to install one of its nine-liter (550 cu in) flathead V12 engines (which would later be developed into the Sunbeam Mohawk) into an automobile chassis in 1913.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Nicknamed "Toodles", the car achieved 114.49 mph (184.25 km/h) at Brooklands before it was shipped to the United States, where it was raced by Ralph DePalma.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Sunbeam also developed a second aero-engined car before World War I, which began life as an Indianapolis 500 racing car before Warwick Wright augmented it with a V8 Sunbeam Sirdar airship engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The car developed 200 brake horsepower (150 kW) at 2,200 rpm, which enabled it to achieve a top speed of approximately 100 mph (160 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] By 1923, this Sunbeam was listed for sale for £1,000.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] By the 1920s, after the end of World War I, interest in and development of aero-engined cars reached a new level.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Coatalen built another aero-engined racing car, the Sunbeam 350HP, which featured a Sunbeam Manitou engine that had been designed to power Royal Naval Air Service flying boats.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] With an engine displacement of 1,118 cubic inches (18.32 L) and the ability to generate 355 hp (265 kW) at 2,100 rpm, the 350HP achieved a top speed of 134 mph (216 km/h) in 1922.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1923, Ernest Eldridge began building the Mefistofele, which consisted of a Fiat SB4 chassis and a 21.7-liter (1,320 cu in) Fiat A.12 bis aircraft engine that produced 320 hp (240 kW) at 1,800 rpm.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] On 12 July 1924, Eldridge drove the car to a world-record speed of 234.980 km/h (146.010 mph) on public roads in Arpajon, France, which marked the last time that a land speed record would be set on public roads.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The car's name was bestowed upon it by the press due to the tremendous amount of noise and smoke generated by its engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Argentine racer Adolfo Scandroglio built his Fiat Botafogo Special in the image of the Mefistofele, using a 1917 Fiat chassis and the same 21.7-liter (1,320 cu in) Fiat A.12 engine that had been chosen by Eldridge.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The car, which was named after a famed racehorse, was capable of producing 320 hp (240 kW) at 1,800 rpm.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1949, Scandroglio was killed while racing the Botafogo Special, and the car was presumed to have been lost before its engine was rediscovered in the 1990s.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] After its rediscovery, the Argentine company Pur Sang, which is noted for creating exact replicas of Alfa Romeo 8C 2300s and Bugatti Type 35s, reconstructed the Botafogo Special.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 2011, the rebuilt car was purchased from Pur Sang by Jay Leno.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1923, the Sunbeam 350HP was purchased by Malcolm Campbell, who made modifications to the coachwork as well as the engine in his endeavor to increase its speed.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] He also renamed the car Blue Bird, and on 25 September 1924 used it to set the official world land speed record with a speed of 146.16 mph (235.22 km/h) at Pendine Sands in Wales.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The next year, on 21 July 1925, Campbell returned to Pendine, where he became the first person to exceed 150 mph (240 km/h) as he set a new record of 150.766 mph (242.634 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Perhaps the most well-known aero-engined cars of the interwar period were the series of amateur, chain-driven creations of Louis Zborowski that were each known as Chitty Bang Bang.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] They later attained fame as the namesake for the children's book *Chitty-Chitty-Bang-Bang*, written by Ian Fleming, as well as the film and musical of the same title.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Although the origin of the name is unknown, it is thought to derive from either a lewd World War I soldier's song or simply the sound of the aircraft engines that powered the cars.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The first car, Chitty 1, featured a customized pre-war Mercedes chassis and a 23-liter (1,400 cu in), six-cylinder Maybach airplane engine that had powered a Gotha G.V bomber before it was surrendered by Germany as a war reparation.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The engine could produce 300 hp (220 kW) at a relatively modest 1,500 rpm.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Chitty 1 achieved celebrity status at Brooklands in 1921, where it won races at speeds in excess of 100 mph (160 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1922, Zborowski returned to Brooklands to achieve his highest ever speed in the car, 113.45 mph (182.58 km/h), although that autumn Chitty 1 was destroyed in a racing accident.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Zborowski began working on a second car of the same name, Chitty 2, in 1921.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] While its use of an older model Mercedes for its chassis made it similar to its predecessor, this iteration of Chitty Bang Bang was powered by an 18.8-liter (1,150 cu in) Benz Bz.IV engine that manufactured 230 hp (170 kW).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Chitty 2 placed second in its only race at Brooklands, although it did record a speed of over 108 mph (174 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1922, Zborowski and his wife took the car on a lengthy excursion across France and Algeria, all the way to the edge of the Sahara, where a dearth of sufficient radiator water caused such substantial engine damage that he was forced to retire the car from racing.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Zborowski himself was killed at Monza while competing in the 1924 Italian Grand Prix, and Chitty 2 passed through a series of owners (including Arthur Conan Doyle) before being acquired by the Crawford Auto-Aviation Collection in Cleveland.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The third of Zborowski's cars, Chitty 3, was also built around a modified Mercedes chassis, this time mated to a six-cylinder Mercedes aircraft engine originally rated at 160 hp (120 kW) that had been tuned to develop 180 hp (130 kW).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Once again, this car raced at Brooklands, where it achieved a top speed of 112.68 mph (181.34 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Zborowski's fourth and final aero-engined car was the Higham Special, which he named in a nod to his manor, the Higham House.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Created in 1924 for the purpose of making an attempt on the land speed record, the car was powered by a World War I V12 Liberty L-12 engine with a displacement of 27 liters (1,648 cu in), which made it the largest-capacity engine to ever race at Brooklands.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] With an engine producing 450 hp (340 kW) and the gearbox and chain-drive of a pre-war Blitzen Benz, the Higham Special achieved a speed of 116 mph (187 km/h) with Zborowski at the wheel.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] After Zborowski's death at Monza, racing enthusiast J.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Parry-Thomas bought the car and, after streamlining the body and modifying the engine, rechristened it "Babs".
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1926, Parry-Thomas took the car back to Brooklands, where he set a new world record with a speed of 129 mph (208 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] He then took Babs to Pendine, where he achieved 169 mph (272 km/h) on the sands.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] After Malcolm Campbell took back the record with a 174 mph (280 km/h) run in his Blue Bird, Parry-Thomas returned to Pendine in 1927 with a more streamlined Babs.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] However, on his first run, he was killed in a crash.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Parry-Thomas' crew buried Babs in the sand, where it remained until Owen Wyn Owen began excavating it in 1969.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Wyn Owen ultimately restored the car to working order by 1985.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 2013, Babs was placed on display at the National Waterfront Museum in Swansea.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1927, Henry Segrave broke Campbell's world speed record with a run of 202.98 mph (326.66 km/h) at Daytona Beach, Florida, in his Sunbeam 1000 hp, which was powered by two V12 Sunbeam Matabele aircraft engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The new record made him the first person to surpass the 200 mph (320 km/h) mark.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The following year, Campbell raced at Daytona to retake the record with a speed of 206.95 mph (333.05 km/h), only to have it eclipsed just two months later by Ray Keech and his Triplex Special, which was powered by three V12 Liberty engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The very next day, while attempting to re-take the record with the Triplex Special, driver Lee Bible lost his life in a fatal crash that also killed a film cameraman.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1931, Campbell returned to competition with an upgraded Blue Bird that was sleeker and lower than its predecessor.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Fitted with a 1,450 hp (1,080 kW) Napier Lion engine, the car successfully set a new land speed record with a run of 246.09 mph (396.04 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] By 1933, Campbell had created another Blue Bird that was powered by a Rolls-Royce R, which had achieved fame as the engine that helped the Supermarine S.6B seaplane win the Schneider Trophy.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] With this engine, which produced 2,500 hp (1,900 kW) and had a displacement of 36.7 liters (2,240 cu in), Blue Bird achieved a speed in excess of 272 mph (438 km/h) at Daytona.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] However, as performance continued to increase, the relatively limited area of Daytona Beach began to prevent cars from reaching their true top speeds.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In September 1935, Campbell took Blue Bird to Utah's Bonneville Salt Flats, where it exceeded 300 mph (480 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Jenkins had his SJ special further modified, replacing the modified SJ engine with a 25.73 liters (1,570 cu in) Curtiss Conqueror engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The Conqueror-engined special was named "Mormon Meteor" by a contest held by the *Deseret News*.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The Mormon Meteor set another 24‑hour record in 1937, averaging 157.27 mph (253.10 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Jenkins then commissioned August Duesenberg to build a chassis that was better able to handle the weight, power, and torque of the Conqueror engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The result was the Mormon Meteor III, which broke the 12‑hour record in 1939 and set a 24‑hour record of 161.18 mph (259.39 km/h) in 1940.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1937, Eyston brought his Thunderbolt to Bonneville, where its twin Rolls-Royce R engines powered it to a world-record speed of 312 mph (502 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] That year on the salt flats, something of a rivalry developed between Eyston and John Cobb, who had previously raced the 23.94-liter (1,461 cu in) Napier-Railton at Brooklands as well as at Bonneville.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] For 1937, Cobb had built the teardrop-shaped, streamlined Railton Special, which featured four-wheel drive and two Napier Lion engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Over the span of just a few weeks, Eyston and his Thunderbolt set a new record of 345.49 mph (556.01 km/h), which Cobb and his Railton Special answered with a run of just over 350 mph (560 km/h), before Eyston retook the title by achieving 357.5 mph (575.3 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The following year, 1938, Cobb returned to Bonneville and set a new world record of 369.7 mph (595.0 km/h), which would stand until 1947 due in part to the hiatus of competition caused by the outbreak of World War II.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Costing an astounding 600,000 Reichsmarks, the six-wheeled, streamlined T80 was largely designed and developed by Ferdinand Porsche.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The T80 was powered by the Daimler-Benz DB 603, an inverted V12 aviation engine that boasted a displacement of 44.5-liter (2,716 cu in) and was capable of producing 2,200 kW (3,000 hp), which had been derived from the Daimler-Benz DB 601 that powered the Messerschmitt Bf 109 fighter aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The T80's engine ran on a fuel mixture that consisted mostly of methyl alcohol (63%), as well as smaller percentages of benzene, ethanol, acetone, nitrobenzene, avgas, and ether.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] After initially being set at 550 km/h (340 mph), the car's targeted top speed was ultimately increased to 750 km/h (470 mph) by late 1939.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] A world speed record attempt was planned for January 1940 on the 10-kilometer (6.2 mi) *Dessauer Rennstrecke* segment of the Reichsautobahn Berlin-Halle/Leipzig, with Stuck at the controls, although the outbreak of World War II prevented the run from ever happening.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] After surviving the war in storage in Carinthia, Austria, the T80 was ultimately acquired by the Mercedes-Benz Museum in Stuttgart.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] After the conclusion of World War II, John Cobb returned to Utah in 1947, where he improved upon his own world record by achieving an official speed of 394.196 mph (634.397 km/h) in his rebuilt Railton Mobil Special.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] On one of the requisite two-way runs, Cobb exceeded 400 mph (640 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Cobb's record would stand for 16 years, and would mark the last time that a piston-engined car would hold the world land speed record.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1951, hot rod and drag racing enthusiast Art Arfons began building a series of aero-engined racing cars each known as the Green Monster.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The first was a two-ton Ford truck chassis mated to an Allison V-1710 piston engine that was altogether capable of a record 144 mph (232 km/h) in a quarter-mile drag race.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Arfons went on to build 12 more piston-engined Green Monsters before he began experimenting with jet engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] First raced in 1960, the Bluebird-Proteus CN7 was built at a cost of £1 million and powered by a Bristol-Siddeley Proteus turboshaft gas turbine engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The engine, which was rated at 4,100 hp (3,100 kW), drove all four wheels.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] After a serious crash at Bonneville, a tail fin was added to the original design before the Bluebird-Proteus CN7 made another run at the world record at Lake Eyre, South Australia.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] There, on 17 July 1964, Donald Campbell piloted the car to a new world record speed of 403.10 mph (648.73 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] A number of other turbine-engined racing cars have been built, including two designed to compete for the world land speed record: Pioneer 2M and the Renault Étoile Filante.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Turbine-engined cars have also raced in other types of motorsports, including both open-wheel racing (Lotus 56 and STP-Paxton Turbocar) as well as sports car racing (Howmet TX and Rover-BRM).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1952, Soviet aircraft designer Aleksey Smolin developed the GAZ-TR, which was powered by a turbojet.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Built in 1954, it was designed to reach 500 km/h (310 mph), but due to the lack of adequate tires and an insufficiently long track it failed to exceed 300 km/h (190 mph) during a test run on November 14, 1954.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The GAZ-TR crashed during testing, injuring driver MA Meteleva and leading to the cancellation of the program.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Wreckage from the car is on display at the GAZ factory museum.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1962, jet engines made their first appearances at Bonneville in three different cars that were each based around the General Electric J47 engine, which also powered the North American F-86 Sabre jet fighter.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] One of the cars was the Flying Caduceus, which was driven to a speed of 331 mph (533 km/h) by Nathan Ostich, a physician who built the first jet car.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The second was piloted by Glenn Leasher, who approached the 400 mph (640 km/h) mark before he was killed in a crash.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The third was the needle-nosed Spirit of America, designed and raced by drag racer Craig Breedlove.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Breedlove also contended for the speed record that year, although he did not capture the title until he recorded a speed of 407 mph (655 km/h) in 1963.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1964, brothers Art and Walt Arfons arrived at Bonneville with jet cars of their own.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Walt had acquired a Westinghouse J46 jet engine, which had been designed for the Vought F7U Cutlass, that he used to power his Wingfoot Express.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Art had opted for a General Electric J79, the same engine that powered the Lockheed F-104 Starfighter and the Convair B-58 Hustler bomber, and built a new, jet-powered Green Monster.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] After Walt Arfons crashed and suffered a heart attack while testing the Wingfoot Express, designer Tom Green was selected to drive the car.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Despite never having driven over 130 mph (210 km/h) before, on 2 October 1964 he piloted the car to a world-record speed of 413 mph (665 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The record stood for just three days, however, before it was broken by Art Arfons and his Green Monster with a speed of 434 mph (698 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Just one week after the Green Monster's record run, Breedlove broke the 500 mph (800 km/h) barrier before surviving a high-speed crash.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The 1964 season ended with Art Arfons retaking the speed title when he made a run at 536 mph (863 km/h) after making modifications to his engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1965, Breedlove returned to the Bonneville Salt Flats with his new Spirit of America - Sonic I, which was powered by a GE J79 engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Challenged by Walt Arfons and his modified, JATO-assisted Wingfoot Express, Breedlove recorded a speed of 555 mph (893 km/h) in his new car.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] While Walt was unable to match Breedlove's speed, his brother Art surpassed it just a week later with a run of 576 mph (927 km/h), despite shredding a tire in the process.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Ultimately it was Breedlove, immortalized by the Beach Boys in the song "Spirit of America", who emerged victorious as he posted a speed of 600.601 mph (966.574 km/h) on 15 November 1965.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1970, Gary Gabelich piloted the rocket-powered Blue Flame to a new world record at Bonneville with a speed of 622.407 mph (1,001.667 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1983, this record was eclipsed by Thrust2, which was powered by a Rolls-Royce Avon jet engine and driven by Richard Noble to a speed of 633.468 mph (1,019.468 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1997, the world land speed record was bested once more by ThrustSSC, which achieved a speed of 763 mph (1,228 km/h) in the Black Rock Desert with Andy Green at the controls.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The car, which was powered by two Rolls-Royce Spey jet engines that manufacture a combined 110,000 hp (82,000 kW) and 50,000 pounds (23,000 kg) of thrust, became the first vehicle to break the sound barrier on land.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Jet-powered drag racing cars have also appeared in National Hot Rod Association (NHRA) events since the 1970s.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Jet cars were first sanctioned by the NHRA in 1974, and in 1980 official approval was granted for jet-powered Funny Cars.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1975, drag racer Phillip "Al" Eierdam created Emergency 1, a jet car powered by a Westinghouse J34 engine and stylized to mimic a fire engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In the 1980s, Eierdam built and raced the rocket-engined Invader, often against his friend Sammy Miller and his rocket-powered Funny Car, Vanishing Point.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The two contested the first side-by-side drag races between rocket-powered cars at Santa Pod Raceway in England.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] By 1989, Roger Gustin had built more jet cars than anyone else in drag racing and had won the Jet Car Nationals on five separate occasions.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In the 2010s, jet cars have continued to be major attractions at NHRA events, participating in exhibitions such as four-wide races and achieving speeds in excess of 270 mph (430 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] During the 2012 season, Elaine Larsen and Marisha Falk both drove jet dragsters powered by General Electric J85 engines capable of producing 5,000 hp (3,700 kW).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Although rare, aircraft engines have occasionally been chosen as the powerplant for road-going cars.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] One prime example is the Tucker 48, which was produced in 1947 and 1948 and powered by a flat-six Franklin O-335 helicopter engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] With a displacement of 5,473 cc (334.0 cu in), the engine produced 166 bhp (124 kW) at 3,200 rpm and produced a maximum of 372 pound-feet (504 N⋅m) of torque at 2,000 rpm, yet due largely to its all-alloy construction only weighed 320 pounds (150 kg).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The engine enabled the Tucker 48 to reach a top speed of approximately 120 mph (190 km/h) and to accelerate from 0 to 60 mph (97 km/h) in 10 seconds.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] While the original O-335 helicopter engine was air-cooled, Tucker engineers modified it to water cooling, which helped improve the powerplant's durability while also giving the car the automotive industry's first fully sealed water-cooling system.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In the 1960s, British engineer Paul Jameson and transmission specialist John Dodd collaborated to build The Beast, a road car fitted with a 27-liter (1,648 cu in) Rolls-Royce Merlin engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Using a General Motors Turbo-Hydramatic gearbox, the back axle from a Jaguar XJ12, doors cast from a Ford Cortina Mk III, and a fiberglass body reminiscent of a Ford Capri, the finished car had a "phallically long front end" that measured 10 feet.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The Beast's engine produced approximately 950 bhp (710 kW) at 2,500 rpm which propelled it to a top speed in excess of 180 mph (290 km/h).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The car averages less than 2 miles per imperial gallon (1.4 L/km).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Once listed by the *Guinness Book of Records* as the world's most powerful road car, by 2012 The Beast had been located in Málaga.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Turbine engines have also been utilized in concept and prototype road cars, such as the three General Motors Firebirds, the Fiat Turbina, and the Chrysler Turbine Car.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1953, the General Motors XP-21 Firebird I became the first car powered by a gas turbine engine to be built in the United States.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Never intended for production, the car was purely a design exercise to determine the feasibility of turbine-powered road cars.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The car's body, which was made of plastic reinforced by fiberglass, was designed by Harley J.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Earl, while its Whirlfire Turbo-Power engine was developed by Charles L.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] McCuen and the GM Research Laboratories Division.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Driving the rear wheels of the car via a conventional transmission, the engine was able to produce 370 hp (280 kW) at 13,000 rpm.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Its successor, Firebird II, debuted at General Motors Motorama in 1956.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In addition to its regenerative gas turbine, the car featured a titanium body, fully independent suspension, power disc brakes, electric gear selection, and air conditioning that could be individually controlled.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The last of GM's Firebirds, Firebird III, was built in 1958.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] It was the only Firebird to influence any GM production cars; both the 1959 and 1961 Cadillac lineups took styling cues from it.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Noted for its extravagant tailfins, Firebird III also broke a number of Earl's styling rules with its very reserved use of chrome and lack of parallel lines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] While GM planned a Firebird IV, it never came to fruition, although the three Firebirds did ultimately become the namesake of the Pontiac Firebird pony cars that debuted in 1967.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1954, Fiat introduced its own experimental turbine-engined prototype, the Turbina.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The car was powered by a two-stage turbine that powered the wheels through a geared reduction unit, while its body was streamlined based on the results of wind tunnel testing.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The Turbina's engine enabled it to achieve a top speed of 250 km/h (160 mph) as well as to produce 300 hp (220 kW) at 22,000 rpm.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Introduced to the public in 1963, the Chrysler Turbine Car was powered by a turbine that produced 130 hp (97 kW) and 425 lb⋅ft (576 N⋅m) of torque, which made its output roughly equivalent to a 318-cubic-inch (5.21 L) V8 engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] However, there were also significant drawbacks with using a turbine engine in the car, namely high internal heat, lack of inherent engine braking, and high emissions of NO x.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Furthermore, the engine was better suited to the relatively continuous operation and constant speeds of aviation use than it was to the more disruptive, stop-and-go conditions of automotive use.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] On the highway, the car could achieve 19 miles per US gallon (0.12 L/km), but because the engine idled at 22,000 rpm it was less efficient in city driving.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Even after the period in which they were competitive in the quest for the world land speed record, there has been continued and renewed interest in piston-driven aero-engined cars.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] One of the earliest cars created during this revival era is the Napier-Bentley, which was built by Peter Morley and David Llewellyn in 1972 in the spirit of the aero-engined cars that raced at Brooklands.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The Napier-Bentley consists of a 1929 Bentley chassis and a 23.9-liter (1,458 cu in) Napier Sea Lion aircraft engine, which produces 580 bhp (430 kW) and 1,250 lb⋅ft (1,690 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The car has been raced regularly, and was once involved in a crash that hospitalized Morley for a few weeks.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 1998, the Napier-Bentley was sold to Chris Williams.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Williams has also designed and built the Packard-Bentley, which he envisioned as a tribute to the interwar aero-engined racing cars that competed at Brooklands.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Built over a period of seven years, the car, which is nicknamed "Mavis", made its debut at the 2010 Cholmondeley Pageant of Power.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The Packard-Bentley is made up of a Bentley 8 Litre chassis and a 40.8-liter (2,490 cu in), V12 Packard engine taken from an American World War II torpedo boat.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The engine gives the car 1,500 bhp (1,100 kW) at 2,400 rpm, while allowing it to achieve a top speed of approximately 160 mph (260 km/h) and a fuel efficiency of four imperial gallons (18 L) per minute.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The Packard-Bentley is valued at around £350,000.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] Aero-engined cars also made an appearance on the British television program *Top Gear* on 4 March 2012, during the sixth episode of Season 18, when both the BMW-engined "Brutus" and Rolls-Royce-engined "Meteor" were featured.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The Brutus was built in Germany shortly after World War II, when a 1908 American LaFrance car was fitted with a 46.9-liter (2,862 cu in) V12 BMW aircraft engine that dates to 1925.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The car was created over several years at a workshop at the Auto & Technik Museum in Sinsheim, Germany, which still owns it.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] According to the Museum, the Brutus can produce 500 hp (370 kW) at 1,500 rpm, while its fuel efficiency averages 1 L/km (2.8 mpg‑imp).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] After driving the car on *Top Gear*, presenter Jeremy Clarkson described the experience as akin to "doing a crossword while being eaten by a tiger".
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The Meteor that appeared during the same episode has the chassis from a 1930s Rolls-Royce Phantom and a World War II-vintage, 27-liter (1,648 cu in) Rolls-Royce Meteor engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] The engine produces 850 bhp (630 kW), which allows the car to achieve a top speed of 160 mph (260 km/h) and a fuel efficiency of roughly 2 mpg‑imp (1.4 L/km).
[src:aircraft-engine/aero-engined-car] In 2013, the Meteor went on sale for a price "in excess of £500,000".
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The **aerospike engine** is a type of rocket engine that maintains its aerodynamic efficiency across a wide range of altitudes.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] It belongs to the class of altitude compensating nozzle engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Aerospike engines were proposed for many single-stage-to-orbit (SSTO) designs.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] They were a contender for the Space Shuttle main engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] However, as of early 2026 no such engine was in commercial production, although some large-scale aerospikes were in testing phases.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The term *aerospike* was originally used for a truncated plug nozzle with a rough conical taper and some gas injection, forming an "air spike" to help make up for the absence of the plug tail.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] However, a full-length plug nozzle may also be called an aerospike.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The purpose of any engine bell is to direct the exhaust of a rocket engine in one direction, generating thrust in the opposite direction.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The exhaust, a high-temperature mix of gases, has an effectively random momentum distribution (i.e., the exhaust pushes in any direction it can).
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] If the exhaust is allowed to escape in this form, only a small part of the flow will be moving in the correct direction and thus contribute to forward thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The bell redirects exhaust moving in the wrong direction so that it generates thrust in the correct direction.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Ambient air pressure also imparts a small pressure against the exhaust, helping to keep it moving in the "right" direction as it exits the engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] As the vehicle travels upward through the atmosphere, ambient air pressure is reduced.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] This causes the thrust-generating exhaust to begin to expand outside the edge of the bell.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Since this exhaust begins traveling in the "wrong" direction (i.e., outward from the main exhaust plume), the efficiency of the engine is reduced as the rocket travels because this escaping exhaust is no longer contributing to the thrust of the engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] An aerospike rocket engine seeks to eliminate this loss of efficiency.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Instead of firing the exhaust out of a small hole in the middle of a bell, an aerospike engine avoids this random distribution by firing along the outside edge of a wedge-shaped protrusion, the "spike", which serves the same function as a traditional engine bell.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The spike forms one side of a "virtual" bell, with the other side being formed by the outside air.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The idea behind the aerospike design is that at low altitude the ambient pressure compresses the exhaust against the spike.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Exhaust recirculation in the base zone of the spike can raise the pressure in that zone to nearly ambient.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Since the pressure in front of the vehicle is ambient, this means that the exhaust at the base of the spike nearly balances out with the drag experienced by the vehicle.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] It gives no overall thrust, but this part of the nozzle also doesn't *lose* thrust by forming a partial vacuum.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The thrust at the base part of the nozzle can be ignored at low altitude.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] As the vehicle climbs to higher altitudes, the air pressure holding the exhaust against the spike decreases, as does the drag in front of the vehicle.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The recirculation zone at the base of the spike maintains the pressure in that zone to a fraction of 1 bar, higher than the near-vacuum in front of the vehicle, thus giving extra thrust as altitude increases.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] This effectively behaves like an "altitude compensator" in that the size of the bell automatically compensates as air pressure falls.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The disadvantages of aerospikes seem to be extra weight for the spike.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Furthermore, the larger cooled area can reduce performance below theoretical levels by reducing the pressure against the nozzle.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Aerospikes work relatively poorly between Mach 1–3, where the airflow around the vehicle has reduced the pressure, thus reducing the thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Several versions of the design exist, differentiated by their shapes.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In the **toroidal aerospike** the spike is bowl-shaped with the exhaust exiting in a ring around the outer rim.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In theory, this requires an infinitely long spike for best efficiency, but a similar effect can be achieved by blowing a small amount of gas out of the center of a shorter truncated spike (like base bleed in an artillery shell).
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In the **linear aerospike** the spike consists of a tapered wedge-shaped plate, with exhaust exiting on either side at the "thick" end.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] This design has the advantage of being stackable, allowing several smaller engines to be placed in a row to make one larger engine while augmenting steering performance with the use of individual engine throttle control.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Rocketdyne conducted a lengthy series of tests in the 1960s on various designs.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Thirty years later their work was revived for use in NASA's X-33 project.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In this case the slightly upgraded J-2S engine machinery was used with a linear spike, creating the **XRS-2200**.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] After more development and considerable testing, this project was cancelled when the X-33's composite fuel tanks repeatedly failed.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Three XRS-2200 engines were built during the X-33 program and underwent testing at NASA's Stennis Space Center.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The single-engine tests were a success, but the program was halted before the testing for the two-engine setup could be completed.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The RS-2200 Linear Aerospike Engine was derived from the XRS-2200.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The RS-2200 was to power the VentureStar single-stage-to-orbit vehicle.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In the latest design, seven RS-2200s producing 542,000 pounds-force (2,410 kN) each would boost the VentureStar into low Earth orbit.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The development on the RS-2200 was formally halted in early 2001 when the X-33 program did not receive Space Launch Initiative funding.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Lockheed Martin chose to not continue the VentureStar program without any funding support from NASA.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] An engine of this type is on outdoor display on the grounds of the NASA Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville Alabama.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The cancellation of the Lockheed Martin X-33 by the federal government in 2001 decreased funding availability, but aerospike engines remain an area of active research.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] For example, a milestone was achieved when a joint academic/industry team from California State University, Long Beach (CSULB) and Garvey Spacecraft Corporation successfully conducted a flight test of a liquid-propellant powered aerospike engine in the Mojave Desert on 20 September 2003.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] CSULB students had developed their Prospector 2 (P-2) rocket using a 1,000 lbf (4.4 kN) LOX/ethanol aerospike engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] This work on aerospike engines continues; Prospector-10, a ten-chamber aerospike engine, was test-fired 25 June 2008.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Further progress came in March 2004 when two successful tests sponsored by the NASA Dryden Flight Research Center using high-power rockets manufactured by Blacksky Corporation, based in Carlsbad, California.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The aerospike nozzles and solid rocket motors were developed and built by the rocket motor division of Cesaroni Technology Incorporated, north of Toronto, Ontario.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The two rockets were solid-fuel powered and fitted with non-truncated toroidal aerospike nozzles.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Flown at the Pecos County Aerospace Development Center, Fort Stockton, Texas, the rockets achieved apogees of 26,000 ft (7,900 m) and speeds of about Mach 1.5.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Small-scale aerospike engine development using a hybrid rocket propellant configuration has been ongoing by members of the Reaction Research Society.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In 2020 the TU Dresden and Fraunhofer IWS started their CFDμSAT-Project for research on additively manufactured aerospike-engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] A prototype has already been tested in a test cell at TU Dresden's Institute of Aerospace Engineering, achieving a burn time of 30 seconds.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In July 2014 Firefly Space Systems announced its planned Alpha launcher that uses an aerospike engine for its first stage.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Intended for the small satellite launch market, it is designed to launch satellites into low-Earth orbit (LEO) at a price of US$8–9 million, much lower than with conventional launchers.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Firefly Alpha 1.0 was designed to carry payloads of up to 400 kilograms (880 lb).
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] It uses carbon composite materials and uses the same basic design for both stages.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The plug-cluster aerospike engine puts out 90,000 pounds-force (400 kN) of thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The engine has a bell-shaped nozzle that has been cut in half, then stretched to form a ring with the half-nozzle now forming the profile of a plug.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The design was abandoned after Firefly Space Systems went bankrupt.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] A new company, Firefly Aerospace, has replaced the aerospike engine with a conventional engine in the Alpha 2.0 design.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] However, the company has proposed Firefly Gamma, a partially reusable spaceplane with aerospike engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In March 2017 ARCA Space Corporation announced their intention to build a single-stage-to-orbit (SSTO) rocket, named Haas 2CA, using a linear aerospike engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The rocket is designed to send up to 100 kg into low-Earth orbit, at a price of US$1 million per launch.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] They later announced that their Executor Aerospike engine would produce 50,500 pounds-force (225 kN) of thrust at sea level and 73,800 pounds-force (328 kN) of thrust in a vacuum.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In June 2017, ARCA announced that they would fly their Demonstrator3 rocket to space, also using a linear aerospike engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] This rocket was designed to test several components of their Haas 2CA at lower cost.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] They announced a flight for August 2017.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In September 2017, ARCA announced that, after being delayed, their linear aerospike engine was ready to perform ground tests and flight tests on a Demonstrator3 rocket.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] On 20 December 2019, ARCA tested the LAS 25DA aerospike steam rocket engine for the Launch Assist System.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Another spike engine concept model, by KSF Space and Interstellar Space in Los Angeles, was designed for orbital vehicle named SATORI.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Due to lack of funding, the concept is still undeveloped.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Rocketstar planned to launch its 3D-printed aerospike rocket to an altitude of 50 miles in February 2019 but canceled the mission three days ahead of liftoff citing safety concerns.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] They are working on a second launch attempt.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In November 2021, Spain-based Pangea Aerospace began hot-fire testing of its small-scale demonstration methane-oxygen aerospike engine DemoP1.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] After successfully testing the demonstrator DemoP1, Pangea plans to up-scale to the 300 kN ARCOS engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Headquartered in Kent, Washington, Stoke Space is building and testing a distributed architecture LH2/LOX aerospike system for its reusable second stage.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The Bremen-based German startup POLARIS Raumflugzeuge GmbH received a Bundeswehr contract to design and flight test a linear aerospike engine in April 2023.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The company is set to test this new engine on board of its fourth spaceplane demonstrator, DEMO-4 MIRA, in late 2023 at Peenemünde, where the V-2 rockets were developed.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The original MIRA demonstrator was catastrophically damaged in a runway accident in February 2024.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] On 29 October 2024, the company was the first ever to ignite an aerospike engine in a flight over the Baltic Sea, powering a four-engine, kerosene-fueled, turbojet MIRA-II demonstrator.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The test involved a three-second burn to collect data with minimal engine stress.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The vehicle achieved an acceleration of 4 m/s2, producing 900 newtons of thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] On 27 February 2025, it was announced that the company had been commissioned by the Bundeswehr procurement office BAAINBw to develop a two-stage, horizontal take-off and fully reusable hypersonic research aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] In addition to its use as a hypersonic testbed and experimental platform for defense-related and scientific research, the aircraft can also be used as a small satellite carrier.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] POLARIS Spaceplanes plans to develop a prototype of a fully reusable spaceplane capable of transporting loads of up to 1,000 kilograms into space by 2028.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Based at the University of Bath, the Bath Rocket Team has been developing their own hybrid rocket engine with an aerospike nozzle since 2020.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The engine was first tested at the UK Race to Space National Propulsion Competition in 2023.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The team is developing a flight-ready version of the engine they are planning to fly for the first time at EuRoC24.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] SpaceFields, incubated at IISc, has successfully tested India's first AeroSpike Rocket Engine at its Challakere facility on 11-Sep-2024.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The engine achieved a peak thrust of 2000N and featured altitude compensation for optimal efficiency.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] Dubai-based LEAP 71 successfully hot fired a 5000N Aerospike powered by cryogenic liquid oxygen (LOX) and kerosene at the test stand of Airborne Engineering in Westcott, UK.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The engine was created through the Noyron Large Computational Engineering Model directly from first principles without human intervention or traditional CAD modeling.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The engine was 3D-printed using selective laser melting as a single monolithic part from a copper alloy (CuCrZr).
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The central spike was cooled using LOX, while the outer jacket was cooled using the fuel.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The injector head measured 600 mm in diameter and a nozzle approximately 1.6 meters tall.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The company claimed that it had progressed from specification to hot-fire in under three weeks creating a dual 20 kN methalox bell-nozzle and aerospike in December 2025.
[src:aircraft-engine/aerospike-engine] The engine was demonstrated with both kerolox and methalox.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] It represents a hybrid class of rocket/ramjet engines, similar to a ramjet, but able to give useful thrust from zero speed, and is also able in some cases to operate outside the atmosphere, with fuel efficiency similar or better than a comparable ramjet or rocket at every point.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] There are a wide variety of variations on the basic concept, and a wide variety of resulting names.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Those that burn additional fuel downstream of the rocket are generally known as ramrockets, rocket-ejector, integral rocket/ramjets or ejector ramjets, whilst those that do not include additional burning are known as ducted rockets or shrouded rockets depending on the details of the expander.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] In a conventional chemical rocket engine, the rocket carries both its fuel and oxidizer in its fuselage.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The chemical reaction between the fuel and the oxidizer produces reactant products which are nominally gases at the pressures and temperatures in the rocket's combustion chamber.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The exhaust is directed rearward through the nozzle, thereby producing a thrust forward.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] In this conventional design, the fuel/oxidizer mixture is both the working mass and energy source that accelerates it.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] It is easy to demonstrate that the best performance is had if the working mass has the lowest molecular weight possible.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Hydrogen, by itself, is the theoretical best rocket fuel.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Mixing this with oxygen in order to burn it lowers the overall performance of the system by raising the mass of the exhaust, as well as greatly increasing the mass that has to be carried aloft – oxygen is much heavier than hydrogen.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] One potential method of increasing the overall performance of the system is to collect either the fuel or the oxidizer during flight.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Fuel is hard to come by in the atmosphere, but oxidizer in the form of gaseous oxygen makes up to 20% of the air.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] There are a number of designs that take advantage of this fact.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] These sorts of systems have been explored in the liquid air cycle engine (LACE).
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Another idea is to collect the working mass.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] With an air-augmented rocket, an otherwise conventional rocket engine is mounted in the center of a long tube, open at the front.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] As the rocket moves through the atmosphere the air enters the front of the tube, where it is compressed via the ram effect.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] As it travels down the tube it is further compressed and mixed with the fuel-rich exhaust from the rocket engine, which heats the air much as a combustor would in a ramjet.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] In this way a fairly small rocket can be used to accelerate a much larger working mass than normal, leading to significantly higher thrust within the atmosphere.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The effectiveness of this simple method can be dramatic.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Typical solid rockets have a specific impulse of about 260 seconds (2.5 kN·s/kg), but using the same fuel in an air-augmented design can improve this to over 500 seconds (4.9 kN·s/kg), a figure unmatched even by high specific impulse hydrolox engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] This design can even be slightly more efficient than a ramjet, as the exhaust from the rocket engine helps compress the air more than a ramjet normally would; this raises the combustion efficiency as a longer, more efficient nozzle can be employed.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Another advantage is that the rocket works even at zero forward speed, whereas a ramjet requires forward motion to feed air into the engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] It might be envisaged that such an increase in performance would be widely deployed, but various issues frequently preclude this.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The intakes of high-speed engines are difficult to design, and require careful positioning on the airframe in order to achieve reasonable performance – in general, the entire airframe needs to be built around the intake design.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Another problem is that the air thins out as the rocket climbs.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Hence, the amount of additional thrust is limited by how fast the rocket climbs.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Finally, the air ducting adds quite a bit of weight which slows the vehicle considerably towards the end of the burn.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The simplest version of an air-augmentation system is found in the shrouded rocket.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] This consists largely of a rocket motor or motors positioned in a duct.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The rocket exhaust entrains the air, pulling it through the duct, while also mixing with it and heating it, causing the pressure to increase downstream of the rocket.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The resulting hot gas is then further expanded through an expanding nozzle.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] A slight variation on the shrouded rocket, the ducted rocket adds only a convergent-divergent nozzle.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] This ensures the combustion takes place at subsonic speeds, improving the range of vehicle speeds where the system remains useful.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The ejector ramjet is a more complex system with potentially higher performance.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Like the shrouded and ducted rocket, the system begins with a rocket engine(s) in an air intake.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] It differs in that the mixed exhaust enters a diffuser, slowing the speed of the airflow to subsonic speeds.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Additional fuel is then injected, burning in this expanded section.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The exhaust of that combustion then enters a convergent-divergent nozzle as in a conventional ramjet, or the ducted rocket case.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] The first serious attempt to make a production air-augmented rocket was the Soviet Gnom rocket design, implemented by Decree 708-336 of the Soviet Ministers of 2 July 1958.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] More recently, about 2002, NASA has re-examined similar technology for the GTX program as part of an effort to develop SSTO spacecraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-augmented-rocket] Air-augmented rockets finally entered mass production in 2016 when the Meteor air-to-air missile was introduced into service.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Plucking a guitar string to induce a vibratory translation is technically a form of propulsion for the guitar string; this is not commonly depicted in this vocabulary, even though human muscles are considered to propel the fingertips.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Technological systems such as motor vehicles typically use one or more engines (motors) as the powerplant, and wheels and axles, propellers or a propulsive nozzle to generate the propulsion.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Drivetrain components such as clutches, gearboxes and drive shafts may be needed to connect the motor to axles, wheels, or propellers.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] In common speech, propulsion is associated with spatial displacement more strongly than locally contained forms of motion, such as rotation or vibration.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The term is derived from two Latin words: *pro*, meaning*before* or *forward*; and *pellere*, meaning *to drive*.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] An aircraft propulsion system generally consists of an aircraft engine and some means to generate thrust, such as a propeller or a propulsive nozzle.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] An aircraft propulsion system must achieve two things.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] First, the thrust from the propulsion system must balance the drag of the airplane when the airplane is cruising.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] And second, the thrust from the propulsion system must exceed the drag of the airplane for the airplane to accelerate.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The greater the difference between the thrust and the drag, called the excess thrust, the faster the airplane will accelerate.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Some aircraft, like airliners and cargo planes, spend most of their life in a cruise condition.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] For these airplanes, excess thrust is not as important as high engine efficiency and low fuel usage.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Since thrust depends on both the amount of gas moved and the velocity, we can generate high thrust by accelerating a large mass of gas by a small amount, or by accelerating a small mass of gas by a large amount.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Because of the aerodynamic efficiency of propellers and fans, it is more fuel efficient to accelerate a large mass by a small amount, which is why high-bypass turbofans and turboprops are commonly used on cargo planes and airliners.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Some aircraft, like fighter planes or experimental high speed aircraft, require very high excess thrust to accelerate quickly and to overcome the high drag associated with high speeds.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] For these airplanes, engine efficiency is not as important as very high thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Modern combat aircraft usually have an afterburner added to a low-bypass turbofan.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Future hypersonic aircraft may use some type of ramjet or rocket propulsion.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Ground propulsion is any mechanism for propelling solid objects along the ground, usually for the purposes of transportation.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The propulsion system often consists of a combination of an engine or motor, a gearbox and wheel and axles in standard applications.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The development of the steam engine and internal combustion engine allowed for the development of rail vehicles and motor vehicles, all of which have some form of a powertrain.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The electric motor allowed for quieter vehicles with lower emissions, and frequently higher engine efficiency.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Maglev (derived from **mag**netic **lev**itation) is a system of transportation that uses magnetic levitation to suspend, guide and propel vehicles with magnets rather than using mechanical methods, such as wheels, axles and bearings.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] With maglev a vehicle is levitated a short distance away from a guide way using magnets to create both lift and thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Maglev vehicles are claimed to move more smoothly and quietly and to require less maintenance than wheeled mass transit systems.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] It is claimed that non-reliance on friction also means that acceleration and deceleration can far surpass that of existing forms of transport.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The power needed for levitation is not a particularly large percentage of the overall energy consumption; most of the power used is needed to overcome air resistance (drag), as with any other high-speed form of transport.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Marine propulsion is the mechanism or system used to generate thrust to move a ship or boat across water.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] While paddles and sails are still used on some smaller boats, most modern ships are propelled by mechanical systems consisting of a motor or engine turning a propeller, or less frequently, in jet drives, an impeller.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Marine engineering is the discipline concerned with the design of marine propulsion systems.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Steam engines were the first mechanical engines used in marine propulsion, but have mostly been replaced by two-stroke or four-stroke diesel engines, outboard motors, and gas turbine engines on faster ships.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Nuclear reactors producing steam are used to propel warships and icebreakers, and there have been attempts to utilize them to power commercial vessels.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Electric motors have been used on submarines and electric boats and have been proposed for energy-efficient propulsion.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Recent development in liquified natural gas (LNG) fueled engines are gaining recognition for their low emissions and cost advantages.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Spacecraft propulsion is any method used to accelerate spacecraft and artificial satellites.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] There are many different methods including pumps.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Each method has drawbacks and advantages, and spacecraft propulsion is an active area of research.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] However, most spacecraft today are propelled by forcing a gas from the back/rear of the vehicle at very high speed through a supersonic de Laval nozzle.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] This sort of engine is called a rocket engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] All current spacecraft use chemical rockets (bipropellant or solid-fuel) for launch, though some (such as the Pegasus rocket and SpaceShipOne) have used air-breathing engines on their first stage.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Most satellites have simple reliable chemical thrusters (often monopropellant rockets) or resistojet rockets for orbital station-keeping and some use momentum wheels for attitude control.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Soviet bloc satellites have used electric propulsion for decades, and newer Western geo-orbiting spacecraft are starting to use them for north–south stationkeeping and orbit raising.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Interplanetary vehicles mostly use chemical rockets as well, although a few have used ion thrusters and Hall-effect thrusters (two different types of electric propulsion) to great success.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] A cable car is any of a variety of transportation systems relying on cables to pull vehicles along or lower them at a steady rate.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The terminology also refers to the vehicles on these systems.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The cable car vehicles are motor-less and engine-less and they are pulled by a cable that is rotated by a motor off-board.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Animal locomotion, which is the act of self-propulsion by an animal, has many manifestations, including running, swimming, jumping and flying.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Animals move for a variety of reasons, such as to find food, a mate, or a suitable microhabitat, and to escape predators.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] For many animals the ability to move is essential to survival and, as a result, selective pressures have shaped the locomotion methods and mechanisms employed by moving organisms.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The study of animal locomotion is typically considered to be a sub-field of biomechanics.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Locomotion requires energy to overcome friction, drag, inertia, and gravity, though in many circumstances some of these factors are negligible.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] In terrestrial environments gravity must be overcome, though the drag of air is much less of an issue.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] In aqueous environments however, friction (or drag) becomes the major challenge, with gravity being less of a concern.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Although animals with natural buoyancy need not expend much energy maintaining vertical position, some will naturally sink and must expend energy to remain afloat.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Drag may also present a problem in flight, and the aerodynamically efficient body shapes of birds highlight this point.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Flight presents a different problem from movement in water however, as there is no way for a living organism to have lower density than air.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Limbless organisms moving on land must often contend with surface friction, but do not usually need to expend significant energy to counteract gravity.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Newton's third law of motion is widely used in the study of animal locomotion: if at rest, to move forward an animal must push something backward.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] Terrestrial animals must push the solid ground; swimming and flying animals must push against a fluid (either water or air).
[src:aircraft-engine/air-propulsion] The effect of forces during locomotion on the design of the skeletal system is also important, as is the interaction between locomotion and muscle physiology, in determining how the structures and effectors of locomotion enable or limit animal movement.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:aircraft-engine/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus originated from **Airbus Industrie GIE**, a consortium of European aerospace companies established in 1970 to produce a wide-body aircraft to compete with American-built airliners.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2000, the consortium's parent firms—Aérospatiale-Matra of France, DASA of Germany, and CASA of Spain—merged to form the **European Aeronautic Defence and Space Company** (**EADS**), which later acquired full ownership of Airbus Industrie.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Reflecting its multinational origins, the company operates offices and assembly plants in France, Germany, Spain, and the United Kingdom, along with more recent additions in Canada, Malaysia, the United States, Morocco, and India.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus's headquarters are legally registered in Leiden, Netherlands, while day-to-day management is conducted from the company's main office in Blagnac, France.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The *SE* in its name denotes *Societas Europaea*, a public company under European Union corporate law.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus is led by CEO Guillaume Faury and is included in the EURO STOXX 50 stock market index.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Since its inception in 2000, the company's shares have been listed on the Paris, Frankfurt, and four Spanish stock exchanges, including the Bolsa de Madrid.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The company traces its origins to the formation of the *Airbus Industrie GIE*, a consortium of European aerospace companies established in 1970 to produce a wide-body aircraft to compete with American-built airliners.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] France's state-owned Aérospatiale owned 37.9% of Airbus Industrie, West Germany's Deutsche Airbus also owned 37.9%, British Aerospace held 20%, and Spain's largely state-owned CASA owned 4.2%.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2000, the European Aeronautic Defence and Space Company (EADS) was established through the merger of Aérospatiale and Matra of France, DASA (the successor to Deutsche Airbus) of Germany, and CASA.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] EADS held 100% of *Eurocopter* *S.A.*, established in 1992 and later renamed Airbus Helicopters, along with 80% of Airbus Industrie GIE, which was quickly reorganised as *Airbus S.A.S.*, a simplified joint-stock company.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2006, EADS acquired the remaining 20% of Airbus S.A.S. from BAE Systems (the successor of British Aerospace).
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] EADS was renamed *Airbus Group N.V.* in 2014 and *Airbus Group S.E.* in 2015.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus S.A.S. and Airbus Group S.E. were merged in January 2017, and in April 2017 the combined entity adopted the name Airbus SE.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Since then, Airbus SE has owned the commercial aircraft manufacturing operations while also serving as the parent company of the other two divisions, Airbus Defence and Space and Airbus Helicopters.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The Airbus product line started with the A300 in 1972, the world's first wide-body, twinjet aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Initial sales were slow, leading to calls to end the Airbus program.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] However, the aircraft would greatly benefit from the 1976 introduction of the ETOPS 90 rule, which allowed twinjet aircraft to operate up to 90 minutes—an increase from 60 minutes—away from the nearest airport.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Under the new rule, the A300 was able to operate over the North Atlantic, the Bay of Bengal, and the Indian Ocean, making it a more efficient alternative to the trijets and four-engined aircraft offered by competitors, leading to renewed airline interest and a sharp increase in sales.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus then developed the A310 to meet demand for a shorter-body but longer-range version of the A300.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The aircraft also introduced a glass cockpit, which eliminated the need for a flight engineer, and a redesigned rear fuselage that used space more efficiently, creating additional capacity.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The A310 was manufactured from 1981 to 1998.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] These design changes were later incorporated into the A300, resulting in the A300-600.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Building on its success with the A300, Airbus developed the narrow-body A320 aircraft that was launched in 1987, which became and remains a major commercial success.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The A320 was the first commercial jet to use a digital fly-by-wire control system.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] All Airbus models developed since have adopted cockpit systems similar to the A320, making it easier for crews to transition between aircraft types.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The success of the A320 led Airbus to introduce a lengthened version, the A321, in 1993, followed by the shorter A319 in 1995 and the even shorter A318 in 2002.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2016, Airbus re-engineered the narrow-body family under a programme called the A320neo (*new engine option*).
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus also embarked on an effort to develop new wide-body aircraft derived from the cross-section of the A300, but with greater range and seating capacity and integrating technologies developed from the A320 programme.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] This effort led to the introduction of the four-engine A340 in 1991 and the twinjet A330 in 1992.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] At that time, Airbus wanted to offer a four-engined jet aircraft to allow for transpacific flights.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] However, during the aircraft's development, new ETOPS rules extended twinjet operations to 120 minutes in 1986 and 180 minutes in 1989.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Although these changes hurt sales of the A340, they greatly benefited the A330.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Production of the A340 ended in 2011, while the A330 was re-engineered as the A330neo (*new engine option*) in 2018.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2005, Airbus introduced the world's largest passenger airliner: the A380 is a four-engine aircraft with two full-length passenger seating decks.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Intended to challenge the dominance of the Boeing 747 in the long-haul market, the A380 was ultimately a money-losing venture for Airbus due to large development costs and limited sales arising from high operating costs, and production ended in December 2021.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The A350, a wide-body, twinjet aircraft, was introduced in 2015.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The A350 was the first Airbus aircraft that was largely produced from carbon-fiber-reinforced polymers.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] It is longer and wider than the fuselage used on the A300, A310, A330, and A340.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] A second narrow-body jet was added to the product list in 2018 when Airbus gained control of the Bombardier CSeries programme, and rebranded it as the A220.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The jet offers five-abreast seating compared to the six-abreast seating on the A320.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In December 2024, it was reported that the total aircraft delivery in the year for Airbus has reached 643 units, with 84 planes delivered in November 2024 alone.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Subsequently, in January 2025, it was reported that Airbus had successfully delivered 766 aircraft to its customers out of 878 orders in the entire 2024, marking a 4% increase from the previous year.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In October 2025, the A320 overtook the Boeing 737 as the most delivered airliner.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus Corporate Jets markets and modifies new aircraft for private and corporate customers.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] It has a model range that parallels the commercial aircraft offered by the company.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Following the entry of the 737-based Boeing Business Jet, Airbus joined the business jet market with the A319 Corporate Jet in 1997.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Although the term Airbus Corporate Jet was initially used only for the A319CJ, it is now often used for all models, including VIP widebodies.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] As of December 2008, 121 corporate and private jets are operating, and 164 aircraft have been ordered.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The company also owns 10% of Dassault Aviation, which builds the Falcon family of smaller business jets.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus Defence and Space markets and either builds or modifies new aircraft for military use.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus became increasingly interested in developing and selling to the military aviation market in the late 1990s.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] It embarked on two main fields of development: aerial refuelling with the Airbus A310 MRTT (Multi-Role Tanker Transport) and later the Airbus A330 MRTT, and tactical airlift with the Airbus A400M Atlas.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The company has also continued to market and assemble some military aircraft previously offered by the companies that formed Airbus, notably CASA.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The A310 and A330-based MRTT aircraft are conversions of civilian airliners.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The aircraft are called multi-role tanker transports because, in addition to their aerial refuelling capability, the aircraft can also be configured for troop transport, medevac, and cargo transportation.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The A400M Atlas is a four-engine, turboprop-powered tactical transport aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The A400M is sized between the American-made C-130 and the C-17 transports, and while it can carry heavier loads than the C-130, its turboprop engines allow it to retain the ability to use rough landing strips.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The A400M was developed for European NATO members Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, Spain, Turkey, and the UK, as an alternative to relying on foreign aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] During development, the A400M programme faced delays and cost overruns; with customer nations stepping in to offer additional subsidies.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The first aircraft was delivered to the French Air Force in 2013, and by 2023, more than 100 aircraft had been built.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The Defence and Space division also markets and assembles the EADS CASA C295, a smaller tactical transport aircraft, that was designed and initially manufactured by the Spanish aerospace company CASA.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus Helicopters builds and markets new rotorcraft for civilian and military use.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The division was founded formed in 1992 as the Eurocopter Group, through the merger of the helicopter divisions of Aérospatiale and DASA (two of the founding companies of Airbus).
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus Helicopters is the foremost player in the turbine helicopter industry in terms of both revenue and deliveries.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The division's civilian products include the single-engine H125 and H130, the light twin-engine H135 and H145, the medium twin-engine H155 and H160, the super medium twin-engine H175, and the heavy twin-engine H215 and H225.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Military products include the Tiger attack helicopter, along with militarised versions of the H125, H135, H145, H160, H175, H215, and H225.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The company owns 62.5% of NHIndustries joint venture, which builds the NH90 military utility helicopter.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Commercial aircraft generated 74% of total revenue for the Airbus group in 2018 and 72% in 2023.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] This line of business was the first one in the world to begin field tests with TETRA Enhanced Data Service (TEDS).
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The Airbus Military division, which manufactured tanker, transport, and mission aircraft; Airbus Helicopters, the world's largest helicopter supplier; Astrium, provided systems for aerial, land, naval, and civilian security applications, including Ariane, Galileo, and Cassidian.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Through Cassidian, EADS was a partner in the Eurofighter consortium as well as in the MBDA missile systems manufacturer.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus Helicopters, formerly known as Eurocopter, is a helicopter manufacturing and support company.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus has several final assembly lines for different models and markets.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus, however, has a number of other plants in different European locations, reflecting its foundation as a consortium.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] For aircraft assembled in Europe, aircraft parts often move between the different factories and the assembly lines via the use of the Beluga and BelugaXL, a fleet modified aircraft capable of carrying entire sections of fuselage.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] For aircraft assembled in China and the United States, the parts needed to build an aircraft meet in a single European location where they are loaded onto ships for the final journey to the assembly line.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus opened an assembly plant for the A320 family of aircraft in Tianjin, China in 2009.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus started constructing a $350 million component manufacturing plant in Harbin, China in July 2009.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] It was fully operational by early 2011, the 30,000 square metre plant manufactures composite parts and assembles composite work-packages for the A350 XWB, A320 families and future Airbus programmes.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Harbin Aircraft Industry Group Corporation, Hafei Aviation Industry Company Ltd, AviChina Industry & Technology and other Chinese partners hold an 80% stake in the plant while Airbus controls the remaining 20%.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2022, the Tianjin plant finished upgrading works to allow for production of A321.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2023, the Tianjin final assembly plant started construction to be expanded with a second production line.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] North America plays a crucial role for Airbus, both in terms of aircraft sales and suppliers.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Of the approximately 5,300 Airbus jetliners sold worldwide, 2,000 are ordered by North American customers.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] These orders span Airbus' entire product line, from the compact A318 to the massive A380, accommodating 107 to 565 passengers.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Notably, US contractors contribute significantly, supporting around 120,000 jobs and generating an estimated $5.5 billion in business.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] For instance, one variant of the A380 boasts 51% American content in terms of work share value.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Plans for a Mobile, Alabama aircraft assembly plant were unveiled by Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier from the Mobile Convention Centre on 2 July 2012.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The plans include a $600 million factory at the Mobile Aeroplex at Brookley for the assembly of the A220, A319, A320 and A321 aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] It could employ up to 1,000 full-time workers when operational.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Construction began on 8 April 2013, and became operable by 2015, producing up to 50 aircraft per year by 2017.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] On 16 December 2024, it was reported that Airbus had leased 650,000 sq ft of office space in Bengaluru's Whitefield to build its Global Capacity Centre.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The lease is for 10 years and valued at Rs 500 crore, securing the entire building in Titanium Tech Park.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In this way, Airbus intends to strengthen its position in India.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In October 2005 the British Ministry of Defence warned European politicians to stop, as it saw it, interfering in the corporate governance of EADS.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The former UK Defence Procurement Minister Lord Drayson hinted that the UK government, a major customer for EADS, may withhold future contracts.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] On 4 April 2006, DaimlerChrysler announced its intention to reduce its shareholding from 30% to 22.5%.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The company placed a value on the stake at "approximately €2.0 billion." Lagardère was to reduce its holding by an identical amount.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] However, Caisse des Dépôts et Consignations, a unit of the French government, acquired 2.25% of EADS.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] At issue, as a result, is the fact that the German and French shareholdings were now in imbalance.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] On 30 August 2006, shortly after the stock price decline caused by the A380 delivery delays, more than 5% of EADS stock was reportedly purchased by the Russian state-owned Vneshtorgbank, bringing its share to nearly 6%.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In December 2007, Vneshtorgbank sold EADS shares to another state-controlled bank, Vnesheconombank.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] EADS shares were to be delivered by Vneshekonombank to the charter capital of JSC United Aircraft Corporation in 2008.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] On 3 October 2006, shortly after EADS admitted further delays in the Airbus 380 programme would cost the company 4.8 billion euros in lost earnings in 2010, EADS shares, traded on the Paris arm of Euronext, were suspended after they surpassed the 10% loss limit.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Trading resumed later in the day with the one-day loss holding at 7%.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2007, Dubai Holding acquired 3.12% of EADS stock, making the Dubai buy-out fund one of the largest institutional shareholders.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2008, EADS had arms sales equivalent to $17.9 billion, which constituted 28% of total revenue.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In April 2013, Daimler sold its shares in EADS.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] As of 31 December 2024, 73.7% of Airbus Group stock is publicly traded on six European stock exchanges (Euronext Paris in France, the Frankfurt Stock Exchange in Germany, and the four regional stock exchanges Bolsa de Madrid, Borsa de Barcelona, Bolsa de Valencia and Bolsa de Bilbao in Spain).
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] 0.6% of the shares are treasury shares owned by Airbus, while the remaining 25.7% are owned by a "Contractual Partnership".
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] SOGEPA is owned by the French State, GZBV is majority owned by the German state-owned investment and development bank KfW, and SEPI is a Spanish state holding company.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In April 2020, Airbus announced that it had cut aircraft production by a third due to the COVID-19 outbreak.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] According to Guillaume Faury, the company was "bleeding cash at an unprecedented speed".
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The recession put its survival at stake and presented the need for deep job cuts throughout all Airbus departments.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] 3,000 workers in France were involved in government-assisted furlough schemes.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus has committed to "Flightpath 2050", an aviation industry plan to reduce noise, CO2, and NOx emissions.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus was the first aerospace business to become ISO 14001 certified, in January 2007; this is a broader certification covering the whole organisation, not just the aircraft it produces.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In association with Honeywell and JetBlue, Airbus has developed an aviation biofuel to reduce pollution and dependence on fossil fuels, claiming that this has the potential to replace up to a third of the world's aviation fuel.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Algae-based biofuel absorbs carbon dioxide during growth and does not compete with food production.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] This alternative may be commercially available by 2030 but algae and other vegetation-based fuels are in an early stage of development, and fuel-bearing algae have been expensive to develop.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus offers delivery flights to airlines using a 10% biofuel blend in standard engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The fuel does not cut carbon emissions but is free of sulphur emissions, which demonstrates that the fuel could be used in commercial flights in unmodified engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In September 2020, Airbus unveiled three liquid hydrogen-fueled "ZEROe" concept aircraft that it claims could become the first commercial zero-emission aircraft, entering service by 2035.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The design includes an aircraft with six eight-bladed removable motors.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] At the Airbus Summit in March 2025, Airbus delivered updates on its development of the ZEROe hydrogen powered aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Boeing has continually protested over "launch aid" and other forms of government aid to Airbus, while Airbus has argued that Boeing receives illegal subsidies through military and research contracts and tax breaks.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In July 2004, former Boeing CEO Harry Stonecipher accused Airbus of abusing a 1992 bilateral EU-US agreement providing for disciplines for large civil aircraft support from governments.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus is given reimbursable launch investment (RLI), called "launch aid" by the US, from European governments, with the money being paid back with interest plus indefinite royalties, but only if the aircraft is a commercial success.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus contends that this system is fully compliant with the 1992 agreement and WTO rules.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The agreement allows up to 33% of the programme cost to be met through government loans, which are to be fully repaid within 17 years with interest and royalties.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] These loans are held at a minimum interest rate equal to the cost of government borrowing plus 0.25%, which would be below market rates available to Airbus without government support.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus claims that since the signature of the EU-US agreement in 1992, it has repaid European governments more than US$6.7 billion and that this is 40% more than it has received.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus argues that the military contracts awarded to Boeing, the second largest US defence contractor, are in effect a form of subsidy, such as the controversy surrounding the Boeing KC-767 military contracting arrangements.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The significant US government support of technology development via NASA also provides significant support to Boeing, as do the large tax breaks offered to Boeing, which some people claim are in violation of the 1992 agreement and WTO rules.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In its recent products such as the 787, Boeing has also been offered direct financial support from local and state governments.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In January 2005 the European Union and United States trade representatives, Peter Mandelson and Robert Zoellick respectively, agreed to talks aimed at resolving the increasing tensions.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] These talks were not successful with the dispute becoming more acrimonious rather than approaching a settlement.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] WTO ruled in August 2010 and in May 2011 that Airbus had received improper government subsidies through loans with below market rates from several European countries.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In a separate ruling in February 2011, WTO found that Boeing had received local and federal aid in violation of WTO rules.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2005 the Government Pension Fund of Norway recommended the exclusion of several companies producing cluster bombs or components.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] EADS and its sister company EADS Finance BV were among them, arguing that EADS manufactures "key components for cluster bombs".
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The criticism was centred around TDA, a joint venture between EADS and Thales S.A.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] TDA produced the mortar ammunition PR Cargo, which can be considered cluster ammunition, however this definition has since been successfully battled by EADS.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] EADS and its subsidiaries are now regarded as fulfilling all the conditions of the Ottawa Treaty.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] According to the new point of view, no product of EADS or its subsidiaries falls into the category of antipersonnel mines as defined by the Ottawa Treaty ("landmines under the Ottawa Treaty").
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In April 2006, the fund declared that the basis for excluding EADS from investments related to the production of cluster munitions is no longer valid, however its shareholding of MBDA means the fund still excludes EADS due to its indirect involvement in nuclear weapons production.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] On 2 June 2006 co-CEO Noël Forgeard and Airbus CEO Gustav Humbert resigned following the controversy caused by the June 2006 announcement that deliveries of the A380 would be delayed by a further six months.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Forgeard was one of a number of executives including Jean-Paul Gut who exercised stock options in November 2005 and March 2006.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] He and twenty-one other executives are under investigation as to whether they knew about the delays in the Airbus A380 project which caused a 26% fall in EADS shares when publicised.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The French government's actions were also under investigation; The state-owned bank Caisse des Dépots et Consignations (CDC) bought part of Lagardère's 7.5% stake in EADS in April 2006, allowing that latter to partially escape the June 2006 losses.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In September 2024, Airbus received negative press attention for its links with Aviation Industry Corporation of China (AVIC), a Chinese company that provides aircraft to the Myanmar junta.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In a joint report, NGOs Justice for Myanmar and Info Birmanie outlined how the supplied aircraft and weapons were used by the Myanmar military to commit war crimes in the Myanmar civil war.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The report called on Airbus to use its influence to pressure the Chinese firm to end its arms sales to the Myanmar junta.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In response to the report, Airbus stated its collaboration focused exclusively on the civil domain, and that its conduct complied with all laws and regulations.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In June 2025, Justice for Myanmar reported that Airbus had completed its divestment from AviChina, AVIC's publicly listed subsidiary, by 1 April 2025.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2003 Tony Yengeni, former chief whip of South Africa's African National Congress, was convicted of fraud worth around US$5 billion relating to an arms deal with South Africa, in which Airbus (formerly EADS) were major players.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] It was claimed that Airbus had admitted that it had "rendered assistance" to around thirty senior officials, including defence force chief General Siphiwe Nyanda, to obtain luxury vehicles.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In March 2003, South Africa withdrew all charges of bribery against the former head of EADS South Africa, and in September 2004, the prosecutor's office dismissed the bribery charges against Yengeni.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In August 2012 the UK's Serious Fraud Office opened a criminal investigation into an EADS subsidiary, GPT Special Project Management Ltd, regarding bribery allegations made by GPT's former programme director, Ian Foxley.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Foxley alleged that luxury cars were bought for senior Saudis, and that millions of pounds sterling were paid to mysterious Cayman Islands companies, possibly to secure a £2 billion contract to renew the Saudi Arabian National Guard's military telecommunications network.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Foxley's allegations were supported by two other GPT employees.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The later agreement between Airbus and the SFO on 31 January 2020 excluded the settlement of this case.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In July 2016, SFO opened a criminal investigation into "suspicions of fraud, bribes and corruption" after Airbus informed British authorities of a failure to disclose the role played by some intermediaries facilitating the sale of aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus was required to provide this information in order to benefit from export credits, which the British, French and German governments had suspended.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In March 2017, the PNF subsequently opened a preliminary investigation into "suspicions of fraud and corruption in civil aviation activities" in cooperation with the SFO.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The allegations included that from 2012 onwards Airbus was responsible for recruiting and remunerating intermediaries to influence the award of civil and military contracts.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Payments worth hundreds of millions of euros in alleged secret commissions were made and numerous sales including in Saudi Arabia, Kazakhstan, Philippines, Indonesia, Austria, China and Mauritius were under suspicion of bribery.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The investigation focused on the Airbus, Strategy and Marketing Organization (SMO), the department responsible for negotiating sales contracts and which, La Tribune reported as having "a network and an incredible influence around the world".
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Directed successively by Jean-Paul Gut and Marwan Lahoud, the SMO was dissolved in 2016 under the new executive director, Thomas Enders, as part of a "clean hands" operation.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In 2014, in a case referred to as the Kazakhgate affair, a search at Airbus Helicopters by French authorities found emails confirming that Airbus had agreed in principle to pay €12 million in bribes to the Prime Minister of Kazakhstan to facilitate the sale of helicopters.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Officers from the Central Anti-Corruption Office (OCLCIFF) then searched the home of Marwan Lahoud on 8 February 2016.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] This revealed that two Turkish intermediaries had claimed payment of commissions due in connection with the sale of 160 aircraft to China valued at US$10 billion.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] A message by Lahoud suggested that the commissions could reach US$250 million.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The SMO was to conceal these commissions as false invoices for a fictitious Caspian pipeline project.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] In January 2020, French, British and American courts validated three agreements between Airbus and the PNF, the UK SFO, and the US DoJ.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus recognised the charges and agreed to pay fines of €2.1 billion in France, €984 million in the United Kingdom and €526 million in the United States.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] The penalties were the highest ever issued by the French and British bodies.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] These settlements close the prosecution of Airbus regarding the Kazakhstan case but not allegations of misconduct in Saudi Arabia, China and Turkey, which Airbus denies.
[src:aircraft-engine/airbus] Airbus managers may still be pursued as private individuals.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:aircraft-engine/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
